>>> ACTION REQUIRED — replace this placeholder with the chosen license <<<

This file is currently a placeholder. The repository is published on
GitHub (github.com/stiftung-humboldtforum/mediensteuerung-probe) but
no license has been formally chosen yet, which means under default
copyright law nobody other than the rights holder may use, modify, or
redistribute the source.

Common options for utility / infrastructure code like this probe:

  - MIT          — short, permissive; allows commercial use,
                   modification, distribution; only requires
                   preserving the copyright notice. Most common
                   choice for small open-source utilities.
                   https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT

  - Apache-2.0   — permissive like MIT but additionally provides an
                   explicit patent license. Recommended for projects
                   that may include patentable algorithms (probably
                   overkill here).
                   https://opensource.org/licenses/Apache-2.0

  - BSD-3-Clause — permissive, similar to MIT, with an additional
                   non-endorsement clause.
                   https://opensource.org/licenses/BSD-3-Clause

  - AGPL-3.0     — strong copyleft; modifications must be released
                   under the same license, including for network-
                   delivered services. Suitable if the Stiftung wants
                   to ensure improvements stay open.
                   https://www.gnu.org/licenses/agpl-3.0.html

  - "All rights reserved" / proprietary — no public license; remove
                   the repo from public visibility on GitHub if this
                   is the intent.

To finalize:
  1. Pick an option (legal counsel of the Stiftung should confirm).
  2. Replace the contents of this file with the verbatim license text
     (e.g. https://choosealicense.com/licenses/mit/).
  3. Update pyproject.toml's missing `license` field accordingly.
  4. Optionally add SPDX-License-Identifier headers to source files.

Until then: third-party DLLs in lib/win32/ have their own licenses
(MPL-2.0 for LibreHardwareMonitor, Apache-2.0 for HidSharp) — those
are documented in lib/win32/LICENSE.txt and are unaffected by this
placeholder.
